If you're on ArgoCD with auto-sync, no manual restart needed — but there's one catch with how Strimzi handles image changes that's worth knowing so you can confirm it actually rolled.

What happens automatically: when the synced `KafkaConnect` CR changes its `spec.image`, the Strimzi operator detects the diff and performs a **rolling restart** of the three Connect pods on its own — one at a time, pulling the new `v3` image. You don't need to delete pods manually. The connectors then reconnect and, because the new image has the MQ plugin classes, they resolve and go Ready.

The catch: Strimzi sometimes doesn't roll pods for an image-only change as promptly as you'd expect, and image-pull caching can mean a pod technically "restarts" but the node serves a stale layer if the tag was ever reused. Two things to verify rather than assume.

First, confirm the CR actually has the new image after sync:

```
oc get kafkaconnect dev-kafka-connect-mq -n dev-kafka -o jsonpath='{.spec.image}{"\n"}'
```

Should print `...kafka-connect-mq:v3`. If it still shows the old image, ArgoCD hasn't synced yet (or auto-sync is off and you need to sync the Application manually).

Second, confirm the pods are actually running the new image, not just restarted:

```
oc get pods -n dev-kafka -l strimzi.io/cluster=dev-kafka-connect-mq \
  -o custom-columns=NAME:.metadata.name,IMAGE:.spec.containers[0].image,AGE:.metadata.creationTimestamp
```

All three should show `v3` and a fresh creation timestamp.

If the operator hasn't rolled them within a couple of minutes of the CR updating, force it:

```
oc delete pod -n dev-kafka -l strimzi.io/cluster=dev-kafka-connect-mq
```

That's safe — the operator recreates them immediately with the new image. (You already did exactly this for the affinity fix and it came back clean.)

Then watch them come up and check the plugins loaded:

```
oc get pods -n dev-kafka -l strimzi.io/cluster=dev-kafka-connect-mq -w
# once Running:
oc exec -n dev-kafka dev-kafka-connect-mq-connect-0 -- find /opt/kafka/plugins -iname "*mq*" 2>/dev/null
```

You should see the IBM MQ source/sink/allclient JARs under `/opt/kafka/plugins/ibm-mq/`. Finally the connectors:

```
oc get kafkaconnector -n dev-kafka
```

The connector CRs themselves don't need a restart — once the workers have the plugin class, the operator reconciles them automatically. If any connector stays `NotReady` after the pods are confirmed on v3, nudge it:

```
oc annotate kafkaconnector neft-mq-source neft-mq-sink rtgs-mq-source rtgs-mq-sink strimzi.io/restart=true -n dev-kafka






